description:
Return how many times the `count++` line would execute for this loop nest with input n:

```
for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
  for (let j = i; j < n; j++) {
    count++;
  }
}
```

The analytical answer is **n(n+1)/2** — confirm by writing a function that returns it directly (no actual nested loop, please — that's the whole point).

**The point**: estimate complexity by counting iterations. Outer i runs n times. Inner j runs n-i times. Total = n + (n-1) + ... + 1 = n(n+1)/2. Even though it looks like 'half' the work, it's still O(n²).

starterCode:
function loopCount(n) {
  // Don't actually run the nested loop — too slow for large n.
  // Return the closed-form n(n+1)/2 in O(1) time.
}

solution:
// O(1) time — direct formula.
function loopCount(n) {
  return (n * (n + 1)) / 2;
}

// Why the loop is n(n+1)/2:
// outer i = 0: inner runs n   times
// outer i = 1: inner runs n-1 times
// ...
// outer i = n-1: inner runs 1 time
// Total: 1 + 2 + ... + n = n(n+1)/2.  Big O: O(n²).
